Did you miss the part in my post where I said no one was forcing his daughter to say the pledge?  If you do not wish to say the pledge, you don't have to say it.  Courts have upheld this before.  Certain religions believe that by saying the pledge, you turn it into an idol and you are, therefore, worshiping the flag.  They teach their children a concept of respecting the flag, but are not allowed to say the pledge in school.  I know several teachers in RL, and one of them has a student who does not say the pledge because of religious beliefs.  This is their right, and the schools don't have any problem with it.  This guy's daughter doesn't say the pledge because of religious beliefs (she's an aethiest).  If she just wanted to say the pledge omitting the &quot;under god&quot;, she could do that too.  It doesn't matter.  But because of this ruling, the guy is taking away other people's rights to say the pledge the way it is written today.  Does no one believe in comprimise anymore?  Or does it always have to be &quot;we're doing it my way and I won't stop until I force you all to do it my way&quot; now days?  The way it is now, we have comprise.  You can say the pledge as it's written, alter it or omit &quot;under god&quot; if you want, or not say it at all.  The other guy just wants to force everyone to do it his way. <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=13891">Creylin McClellan, Dwarven Warlord</a><BR>
